05791nam a22009495i 9781512824278DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128242787 a10.9783/97815128242782doi  a(DE-B1597)642291  a(OCoLC)1356575650  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aJewett, Sarah Orne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Marsh Island /cSarah Orne Jewett; ed. by Don James McLaughlin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQ19: The Queer American Nineteenth Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditor’s Note -- tIntroduction • The Unbounded Terrain of Companionship in Sarah Orne Jewett’s “Best Story” -- tA Marsh Island -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToward the end of her life, Sarah Orne Jewett (1849–1909) made a surprising disclosure. Instead of the critically lauded The Country of the Pointed Firs, Jewett declared her “best story” to be A Marsh Island (1885), a little-known novel. Why? One reason is that it demonstrates Jewett’s range. Known primarily for her vignettes, Jewett accomplished in these pages a truly great novel. Undoubtedly, another reason lies in the novel’s themes of queer kinship and same-sex domesticity, as enjoyed by the flamboyant protagonist Dick Dale. Written a few years into Jewett’s decades-long companionship with Annie Fields, A Marsh Island echoes Jewett’s determination to split time between her family home in Maine and Fields’s place on Charles Street in Boston. The novel follows the adventures of Dale, a Manhattanite landscape painter in the Great Marsh of northeastern Massachusetts and envisions the latter region’s saltmarsh as a figure for dynamic selfhood: the ever-shifting boundaries between land and sea a model for valuing both individuality and a porous openness to the gifts of others.Jewett’s works played a major role in popularizing the genre of American regionalism and has garnered praise, both in her time and ours, for her skill in rendering the local landscapes and fishing villages along or near the coasts of New England. Just as Jewett brought attention to the unique beauty and value of the Great marsh region, editor Don James McLaughlin reveals a convergence of regionalism and sexuality in Jewett’s work in his introduction. A Marsh Island reminds us that queer kinship has a long tradition of being extended to incorporate queer ecological belonging, and that the meaning of “companionship” itself is enriched when we acknowledge its indebtedness to environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtistsvFiction. 0aSalt marshesvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAnnie Fields.  aBoston marriage.  aLGBTQ literature.  aMaine.  aMassachusetts.  aNew England.  aQueer kinship.  aSalt Marsh.  aSarah Orne Jewett.  aamerican literature.  aartist’s studio.  aautobiographical autobiography.  acity slicker.  aecocriticism.  agender.  aghost story.  ahistory of sexuality.  alandscape.  alocal color.  aneglected work.  anineteenth century.  anovel.  aoutsider.  aqueer ecology.  aregionalism.  arural.  awomen writers.1 aMcLaughlin, Don James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLaughlin, Don James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part 